ld French <i>avrill</i>, Latin <i>aprīlis</i>, perhaps with reference to freshness of temperament, or youth, or possibly to the changeable weather of the month.","perhaps occasionally a habitational name from Haverhill in Suffolk, with loss of initial <i>H-</i>. The placename derives from either Old English <i>hæfera</i> ‘oats’ or <i>hæfer</i> ‘he-goat’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. Compare   Avery  ."]}]},{"name":"Julia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine form of the old Roman family name   Julius .  A woman called Julia is mentioned in Paul's Epistle to the Romans (Romans 16:15), and the name was borne by numerous early saints. Its frequency increased with the vogue for classical names in the 18th century, and it continues to enjoy considerable popularity, although the recent introduction of   Julie   to the English-speaking world has reduced this somewhat. Well-known bearers include the British actress  Julia Foster  (  b. 1941 ) and American actress  Julia Roberts  (  b. 1967  as  Julie Fiona Roberts )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Julia De Avenell was born in 1230, in England, United Kingdom, her father, Nicholas De Avenell, was 30 and her mother, Mrs. Nicholas De Avenell, was 31. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with William Wyckhurst Atte Wode."},"et":{"1230–":"1230–Surnud","1230–1264":"1230–1264","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1224–1278":"1224–1278","1245–1313":"1245–1313","1257–1309":"1257–1309","1200–1253":"1200–1253","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1313":"1313","1257":"1257","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","1253":"1253","1264":"1264","1230":"1230","1309":"1309","Hooley House, Coulsdon, Surrey, England":"Hooley House, Surrey, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stevington, City of Bedford, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stevington, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1230–":"1230–Kuollut"